{"key":"post-6336833","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>6336833</id>\n<content>By the way, the reason for NOT shaking at inoculation is when the spores are widely diffused in a substrate, you force the slower growing monokaryons to travel long distances to find a compatible hyphae to pair up with, slowing down the whole process.  If you don't shake, your mycelium can look for a girlfriend right in the same area it germinates in, speeding up the process because dikaryons grow much faster than monokaryons.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>6336983</next>\n<prev>6336823</prev>\n<first>6336614</first>\n<last>6343113</last>\n<when>1165354658</when>\n<utime>12/05/06 11:37 PM</utime>\n</post>"}